                               -= Gems =-
 
Want fast and simple treasure for your mobs?  Something that doesn't
LOOK like it's the same stuff, over and over again?  Have we got the
answer for you!
 
The basic gem object would look like this:
 
#include <mudlib.h>
inherit STD_GEM;
 
void reset(int iArg) {
  if(!is_clone(this_object())) return;
  ::reset(iArg);
  if (iArg) return;
  set_gem_type("something");
}
 
 
Woo!  TEN LINES!  That's it!  If you put that literal code in, you would
get one of over fifty random gems (more than 200 counting all the color
variations, etc.) every time you cloned it.  Let's get into some specifics,
now.
 
Listed below are the 6 gem catagories (and average selling prices) and the
gem varieties in each.
 
Jewel     (1125)
-----
        diamond                 emerald
        ruby                    star ruby
 
Gemstone   (900)
--------
        fire opal               jacinth
        opal                    sapphire
        star sapphire
 
Precious   (600)
--------
        amethyst                aquamarine
        garnet                  pearl
        peridont                spinel
        topaz
 
Fancy      (300)
-----
        alexandrite             amber
        beryl                   cat's eye
        chrysoberyl             coral
        hawk's eye              jade
        jet                     tourmaline
 
Semiprecious   (120)
------------
        bloodstone              carnelian
        carnelian onyx          chalcedony
        chrysoprase             citrine
        hyacinth                jasper
        moonstone               onyx
        sardonyx                star rose quartz
        sunstone                zircon
 
Ornamental      (40)
----------
        azurite                 banded agate
        hematite                lapis lazuli
        malachite               moss agate
        obsidian                quartz crystal
        rhodochrosite           serpentine
        tiger eye agate         turquoise
 
Each of these also have associated random values: colors, markings, and the
like, and will be randomly assigned.
 
So, instead of "something" in the above example, you can put a SPECIFIC stone
(IE, "lapis lazuli"), and get a fine specimen of that stone.  Or, you can put
the catagory (IE, "jewel") and get a random stone from that catagory.
 
 
Functions for this object:
 
set_gem_type("string");
  As listed above, you can put an actual gem name (refer to the lists), or a
  gem catagory.  Anything else will generate a random gem from the entire
  pool. THIS FUNCTION MUST BE SET FIRST!!!!  (otherwise, it will overwrite
  anything you try to set.)
 
  Valid gem types are:
  "jewel", "gemstone", "precious", "fancy", "semiprecious", "ornamental"
  or, an individual gem name.  Anything else will give you a random gem,
  rather than returning an error.  Nice, huh?
 
  This function doesn't recognize multiple arguments.  If you want (for
  example) either a jewel OR a gemstone, use a switch in your code. :)
 
add_value(amt);
  This will allow you to set an added amount (positive or negative integer
  value) to the generated value.
 
set_flawless(int);
  This an integer value; a positive value will guarantee an above average
  gem, a negative value will guarantee a below average gem, and 0 will
  restrict the gem to a value in the average range.
 
 
These are all you need, but if you need to personalize a particular gem, the
standard functions as follows are all still available.  Defaults are shown
below.
 
set_short("Description here");
  If you don't set this, it will show as: A <color> <name of gem>.
 
set_long("Set the long description here.\n");
  If you don't set this, it will show as:
      A <description> <gem name> <still more description!>.
  Basically, you'll have a real description, rather than "you see nothing
  unusual."
 
set_name("name");
  This is set to the name of the gem.
 
set_alt_name("name");
  This is set to a single word for the gem, in most cases the name of the gem
  is used here.  In others, such as 'tiger eye agate', part of the name
  is used, ie: 'agate'.
 
set_alias("name");
  This is set to "gem" in all cases.
 
set_weight(int);
  This is set to 1.
 
set_treasure_type(TYP_GEM);
  You PROBABLY don't need to change this.  If you do want to add another
  type, be sure to include (TYP_GEM|whatever).
 
set_material(MAT_GEM);
  Ditto, you PROBABLY don't need to change this.
 
set_value(int);
  DON'T use this function, except in rare cases; use add_value() or
  set_flawless() to adjust the value. This is calculated automatically based
  on the catagory of gem, with a randomly generated modifier for quality
  (heavily weighted towards the middle, but allowing for WIDE variations).
 
set_info("string.\n")
  Based on the previously-mentioned quality modifier, this will be set to one
  of the following strings (from worst to best):
    This gem is horribly flawed!
    This gem is somewhat flawed.
    This gem has no apparent flaws.
    This gem is flawless.
    This gem is absolutely flawless!
 
 
